  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Recommends policies and practices to combat financial crimes\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides guidelines for international cooperation in preventing money laundering\n- Encourages countries to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes principles for bank supervision and AML practices\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Provides recommendations for preventing money laundering\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (U.S. law with international implications)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n6. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Set regulatory standards for EU member states\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
